The only scenario in which a PM would be chosen sooner is if either Johnson or Hunt drop out. Johnson would have to come under serious heat to consider dropping out due to the fact that he is the overwhelming favorite to win, has been waiting for this moment for over a decade and is notoriously stubborn. Furthermore, he is well known for his eccentric personality and pension to say ridiculous things, thereby and has proven that controversies are hard to stick on him. Hunt is far more likely to drop out of the race due to a controversy or fading chances. However, He has alreadry signalled his willingness to stick it out promising Boris Johnson "the fight of his life". Moreover, his term as Health Secretary was fraught with controversy, and he remained in office, showing that Hunt too is someone who works through controversy. Finally, this resignation would have to happen within 9 days, before any conservative member would have a chance to vote. There has been an argument put forward that no time can be lost replacing the PM because of the urgency with reopening negotiations with the EU. When the EU warned the UK not to waste the extra time they had (to 31st October) to leave the EU, they did not mean the UK had extra time to negotiate a new Withdrawal Agreement, they meant there was extra time for the UK Government to figure out how to get the WA that had already been agreed thru Parliament. As none of the candidates remaining have even mentioned the possibility of getting the current WA thru Parliament and are basing their tactics on forcing the EU to reopen the WA there is not really any rush to get the new PM in place, as the EU have made it clear that WA negotiations are over and the EU is busy sorting out who the EU Commission is going to be made up of from November. I doubt that Barnier would want to give the UK a Brexit renegotiation when he has no authority and he is busy trying to get a higher job. This confusion (ignorance) is typical of the UK's dealings with the EU, they seem to be incapable of understanding what those on the other side of the table will or can do, or what they want. Its very odd that the candidates for PM all claim to be expert negotiators but appear to have no idea how getting people to agree with you works. The same can be said of Trump of course (did I miss the Trump deals on the Middle East peace, made Iran behave, turned North Korea into a peaceful non-nuclear democracy, made America Great Again etc?)

The question is one if timing (before July 1). From Economist: “This week Conservative MPs will winnow down to two the candidates to be their party leader—and thus Britain’s new prime minister. Boris Johnson begins the week as the overwhelming favourite but with his credibility damaged by his refusal to appear in a television debate on Sunday. Today Tory MPs hold closed-door hustings; tomorrow there will be a secret ballot to eliminate the least popular candidates (who need at least 33 votes to survive). The (probably five) remaining then appear in a second TV debate; this time Mr Johnson has deigned to take part. The prime-ministerial hopefuls have all shown an alarming tendency to embrace economic incompetence. Most are prepared to see the country crash out of the European Union without a deal. And they are proposing huge tax giveaways, often directly to their supporters. That is because the party’s 160,000 members—overwhelmingly white, male, affluent, Brexity and old—get the final say on whom to anoint.“

Reducing ‘no’ from 75%. @Tetbury makes a good argument [1] that Tories may want to go through the full process (including voting by all members) to make sure candidates get to share and defend their views and that the party properly deliberates before picking PM given how high the stakes are.

After the first round of MPs voting some commentators (and Conservative MPs) suggested that Johnson was so far ahead that the process could be speeded up by getting several candidates to withdraw and getting down to the last two earlier than planned and then cutting the time for Party Member to vote, or have the second most popular candidate agree to step down if Johnson was well ahead. The idea being that an an acclimation rather than more voting was good for party solidarity. But that did not work out well with Mrs May, so they seem to now be trying to slow the process and trying to keep candidates in the running, so that the members do get to vote and the candidates do have to explain their plans. (As most candidates don't seem to know the difference between a plan and an aspiration I wish them luck with finding out any plans for Brexit apart from telling the EU to drop the Irish Backstop or put an end date on it.)

While the 1922 Committee has changed the rules to attempt to hurry along the Conservative leadership contest, it seems that a final result will not be in place till July. To run for the leadership a candidate must now be backed by at least 8 members of the Conservative parliamentary group. In the second and third round a candidate must receive, respectively, 5% and 10% of the available votes to continue. The final candidates are then expected to have been found around June 20. However, then all members of the Conservative parties will need to vote for their desired candidate and this part of the process is not expected to be finalized until July 22nd. Hence, it seems extremely unlikely that a new PM will take office before July 1st . I adjust probabilities accordingly.

After Theresa May's resignation this week the United Kingdom will have to find a new Prime Minister. The conservative party will have to find a new party leader who then will also become the UK's prime minister, as the conservative party is the ruling party currently, so the party with the majority in the government. The party leader will have to be elected by the members of the conservative party, which are about 130.000. The new prime minister will then have to be elected by the government only (so not the public), with almost certain probability a conservative candidate will be elected as next prime minister of the UK (https://www.bbc.co.uk/newsround/48446564).

Update: According to the BBC (June 7, 2019), the results of the upcoming leadership contest will be announced the week July 22 -- allowing time for secret MP voting and Conservative member voting on the next leader. This means that as of July 1, Theresa May stands to be Prime Minister of the UK.

From the Economist: Theresa May resigns today as Conservative Party leader, after failing to get her Brexit plan through Parliament. She will continue as Britain’s prime minister until a new party leader is chosen. The contest kicks off on June 10th. Eleven Tory MPs have already put themselves forward, but the party’s 1922 Committee, which supervises the race, says each must have the support of at least eight other lawmakers to stand. The parliamentary party then holds a series of votes to whittle the number down to two. In late June these two go to a postal ballot of 124,000 party members—who tend to be older and more vehement Brexiteers than the general population. That makes Boris Johnson, who says he is perfectly prepared to leave the European Union without a deal, the front-runner to inherit the prime ministership. Whoever wins will have little time to resolve Brexit, as the latest deadline for it is October 31st.“ The process and timing seem anachronistic.

I agree with what @mariam said yesterday, it looks as Mrs May will have to go, but the manner of her going is not definite. Many Conservatives are said to think that if she goes before the EU Parliamentary Election 23rd May that would be a much needed boost for Conservative candidates. But if she goes before or after the election, as far as this question is concerned, the important issue is if she is pushed by her own MPs to resign immediately or she just agrees to resign asap. When Cameron resigned replacing him with May took just under 3 weeks, but this time there is likely to be a lot more candidates, so whittling down to two will presumably take at least a few days more. And in 2016 after the MPs had reduced the candidates to 2, the other candidate (Leadsom) pulled out. If the full election process had been followed I thing it would have taken over a week and more like two weeks to have organised the required vote for all party members. So I would guess that from May announcing she was resigning to a new PM taking over would take it would probably take at least 5 or 6 weeks. There is less than 7 weeks until this question ends. It would be possible to do it faster, but presumably they would be more interested in making sure the next PM was the best person, than they would in rushing the process. The other possibility would be installing a temporary PM (who would be the new PM as far as this question is concerned) to give more time to choose the permanent replacement, but I don't see what the point would be. A temporary PM would not have authority to do anything apart from maintaining the status quo (and the EU would not want to negotiate Brexit with him/her). It could be close but if May resigns this week there is a 50% chance there will be a New Conservative PM before 1st July and for every day after that the chances drop by about 1%. We will soon find out, but Mrs May will probably last long enough that a replacement is not in office until after the end of June. (There is probably no rush, because if a new PM fancies a different EU WA that has been agreed already with the EU I doubt that the EU would be able to renegotiate before November and to do that A50 woud need to be delayed again. There are not really any good options for anyone who becomes the next PM.)

Based on the existing evidence. UK PM Theresa May and EU leaders negotiated a delay in March and April 2019 for UK withdrawal from EU, but later the deadline extended to October 2019. In the meantime, Theresa May has stated her intention to resign as PM once the UK withdraws itself from EU successfully. The bill would have to pass through both lower House of Commons and upper House of Lords to ratify the deal and leave the EU, and the UK need to take part in the European elections in terms of the EU membership on May 23. If Parliament cannot agree on a deal soon and the UK does not take part in the European elections on 23 May, then a no-deal would happen on 1st June. If the elections take place, then the final line is 31st October. Thus, the UK would have to leave the EU in June without a deal.

It is likely that Theresa Mays foes actually want her to be scapegoated with as much baggage as possible and will want her to continue for the time being so that they can strategise and kick her out once as much damage and blame can be laid at her doorstep and hard decisions can't be inherited any more. However, a very possible very poor showing in the European elections could make the the negative noise around her so great that it will be seen by Theresa May as the reason to step down and for her foes to go in for the kill (against some of their own desires to wait) and she could step down swiftly for the sake of Brexit and her party. However, she is likely to resist this in the belief that a transition to a new leader without any form of a deal would be too much of a self inflicted wound at such a vulnerable and critical moment. She will weigh what will be the greatest cause of weakness, the noise around her or a transition to a new leader and ultimately her decision will be based on this. It could be quite likely that a strong Labour showing (possibly double the vote of the Conservatives based on initial polling) will make her position untenable and she will leave. She would be blamed for this good showing by her actions in legitimising Labour and their Brexit ideas by reaching out to them for a deal. May cannot be forced to step down as party leader until the end of the year, and I doubt she would hold a general election for fear of losing more seats and potentially allowing Labour a majority. She has shown that she is incredibly inflexible and obdurate, so I do not think she will step down until either she is forced to, or some resolution has been reached on Brexit so that she can consider her job done. I think it is unlikely that either of these will happen sufficiently soon for her to be replaced by 1 July (partly because I think it would make more sense for either an election or a leadership contest to take place during the summer recess, which begins on 24 July). Therefore, I think by far the most likely outcome is that she will be in power on 1 July (though if there is either an election or a leadership contest I think she would, in practice, more or less have to stand down). If she is replaced, it is far more likely to be because she stood down as party leader than because she triggered an election, and in that case there would automatically be a Conservative replacement. And even if an election is called, it is not at all clear that Labour would claim a majority, so for those two reasons the probability of a Conservative replacement must be significantly higher than the probability of a Labour replacement. I think the prospect of a non Labour/Conservative replacement is practically zero, but have said 1% as I can't really say that there is no possibility whatsoever of that happening.

As base-rate for the forecast at hand serves the history of Prime Minister resignations in the UK since 1945. In total, 8 of the 13 Prime Ministers (62%) that governed the UK after 1945 had to leave office before the regular end of their respective terms. Only one resignation was the product of a no-confidence vote and a party switch in the government after a corresponding general election. In the other 7 cases the prime ministers that took over office from the resigning precursors were members of the same party. While three of the PM resignations were connected to individual issues, such as health or scandals, the vast majority, namely 5 were related to major political decisions, 1 domestic and 4 international. Particular, interesting is that the international-related resignations were related to issues concerning either the Middle-East or Europe.

Mrs May's position has deteriorated considerably in the last 24 hours. Her attempt to directly address the "people" and blame parliament for the Brexit mess went down very badly with MPs, and it is the votes of the MPs, not the "people" that she needs to get her WA through parliament. MPs were angry that May said that MPs had not said what they wanted, just what they did not want, when it has been Mrs May who has been blocking them from having free votes on any options (free votes being ones where MPs are allowed to vote according to what they think as opposed to whipped votes where they have to vote according to party directions.) The EU has upped the anti by taking Mrs May at her word (that she would not agree to a long extension) and offering only a shorter extension that she asked for (to May 22nd not June 30th) and said no further extension to that could happen. I might be completely deluded, but this looks like negotiating tactics by both Mrs May and the EU. Both want to see who blinks first; the EU, Mrs May or MPs. Polling shows that the UK public blame the UK government for the mess and Mrs May specifically. An online petition from UK voters to parliament calling for A50 to be revoked has been crashing all day because of an unprecedented volume of traffic. Parliament has now rejected the WA twice and instructed Mrs May to avoid a No Deal. It is possible but very unlikely that parliament will cave in and now vote for what MPs have already judged to be bad deal. And some of those who voted against the WA want no deal, so are not going to change their votes to avoid no deal. The EU is very unlikely to back down. Parliament might take control of events from Mrs May in the next few days. It is believed that the EU would agree to a long extension of A50 if for good reason, but if Mrs May refuses to request it then MPs could (without needing government permission or the PMs agreement) revoke A50 (a court case established in was in parliaments power). The bottom line is that its difficult to see how May can survive unless she get her WA voted through.

Theresa May showed her resilience even after two votes of non-confidence, both from the Labour Party (https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/theresa-may-no-confidence-vote-result-jeremy-corbyn-election-brexit-deal-conservative-labour-a8731331.html and https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2019/jan/16/mays-government-survives-no-confidence-vote-after-brexit-defeat) and her own party (https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-46547246). This is the most time accurate, geographical and situational baseline that can be find on this forecast. Nevertheless, in the next days a unique event will see its final phases, namely Brexit. The day in which it will happen - as analyzed in the forecast about the Article 50's extension - depends basically from Theresa May's ability to draft a program for Brexit which finds the Parliament's agreement. Her success or failure in driving her country into a successful or failing Brexit will determine much of her resilience as Prime Minister. If the Brexit process will be moved after the 1 July, it's unlikely that she will have to face another non-confidence vote, as at least her party can't constitutionally invoke another no-confidence vote until next December (I would give this outcome a 60% probability, in line with the already mentioned forecast). If Brexit will happen before the 1st of July, there's going to be a no-deal Brexit or a Brexit based on a deal the UK Parliament didn't like at all (https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-politics-47547887). In both cases, it is very unlikely that Theresa May will stay in her position (I would say a 10% probability). Adding this last case with the probability of the Brexit deal to be postponed (60%), it's explained why I gave a 70% probabilty to the no answer to the forecast. Let's now move to the cluster of possibilities deriving from the possibility of Thresa May being removed from her office. The UK's electoral system, without explaining the details, basically advantages the big parties, which is the reason why from the very beginning of the elections in this country only two factions basically had an alternance to the government (at the beginning the division was Tories-Whigs, nowadays it's Liberal-Conservatives, https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_United_Kingdom_general_elections). Both the major parties showed their fluctuating trust in Theresa May, but I think it's much more likely that, in case of Theresa May deposed from her office, the opposite party she represent will form a new goverment.

Any normal person would have already resigned when faced with the public humiliation of her Brexit plans being voted down by a record vote. Adjusted decision tree from previous forecast: https://www.gjopen.com/comments/comments/799464 There have been no votes of no confidence before the actual vote on the deal tomorrow, so I am working off these assumptions: I give the Brexit deal passing tomorrow a probability of 20% (adjusting down from 65% previously, my assumption that there would be a vote of no confidence earlier was wrong). I think if the deal passes, May would would stay. If the deal fails to pass, there are 3 days to come up with the so-called 'Plan B', but I don't think there is much ground to be gained with the EU in that timeframe. So I actually see 'Plan B' failing to pass the Commons at 90% probability, factoring in that there might not even be a vote. What could change that is May threatening the no deal scenario, but I would think that she would face a vote of no confidence soon after that attempt. With plan B rejected, think it is certain that a vote of no confidence that allows for general elections in time before the question closes will follow. Given a vote of no confidence in time, I see a 95% probability of May/the government loosing that vote (in this scenario neither the deal nor Plan B passed). For general elections, I reduced the chance of a PM from neither big parties to 0, and have Labour and Conservatives at 50:50 to win the election, in line with polling data that shows them very close. Following the branches and some arithmetic gives me the forecast.

In order to have a PM from the Labour Party, Labour would need to win a General Election. If there was a General Election today, and Labour ran with the leader it currently has (Corbyn) and with a manifesto that is the same as its current policy (which includes "to deliver Brexit") it difficult to see how it could get more seats in parliament than it has now. Corbyn is seen by those who did not vote Labour in the 2017 as a good example of a 1960s socialist who has had no new ideas in the last 50 years, and is incapable of responding to the world of today. If they had felt Corbyn had anything to offer then they would have voted Labour in 2017. On the other hand there is a growing number of people who voted Labour in 2017 hoping that Corbyn really believed in letting Labour Party Members set the parties policies. but It has become clear that Corbyn's belief in policies set by the people, is as sincerely held by him as it was by Chairman Mao, Stalin, and Mrs May (i.e. the "people's" best interests are better served by an all knowing leader, than by taking any notice of the "people") The advantage the Conservatives should have if an election were called before July is that presumably they would not be lead by Mrs May, who shares many of the faults that Corbyn has (does not know how to listen and change her policies, or how to lead - by which I mean, the ability to understand an issue, work with experts to formulate a possible solution and then sell that solution to people who had different ideas, in order that the solution is implemented.) In an election of Corbyn vs May the ineptitude of both would cancel each other out and the result could go either way, although Corbyn would have the advantage that as he has never held any government post voters have not had concrete evidence of how bad he would be. May on the other hand has been PM and there is lots of evidence how bad she is. So in an election without May the Conservatives could have picked a competent leader with some ideas, which would be a great advantage and could attract wide support and give them a win. But the chances are that the Conservatives could replace May by leader who is as bad as May, and if the Conservative Party Members get their say they would likely pick someone as leader who is a lot worse, and would appeal to no one except the (few) Conservative Party Member. As Conservative MPs are (slightly) more sensible that the Conservative Members they will do all they can to avoid letting the Members pick a new leader. The easiest way to do this is refuse to vote for a General Election. Therefore my conclusion is that unless May resigns she will remain as PM because the only way to get rid of her by July would be for Conservative MPs to join the opposition in voting her out. They will not want to vote her out in fear of a worse leader (the Leavers fear another Remainer, Remainers fear a Leaver). If the Conservatives are forced to elect a new leader then its a 50/50 chance that leader will have very little appeal to the wider electorate.

Having the UK Government lose two votes in two days indicates that Mrs May is losing control. In both cases May was defeated due to senior Conservatives working with opposition parties. In normal circumstances a PM would be expected to resign if this were to happen. Mrs May's argument over the last six months is that there is no other plan than to vote for her deal. Today's amendment, that was passed, requires her to present an alternative plan within three (working) days of losing the vote on her Brexit Deal. The expectation is that that vote will occur next Tuesday and that May will lose it. Therefore she would need to present a new plan of action to parliament by 21st Jan. There are several things that could happen; (a) May could present a new plan, but a vote of no confidence in the government is called (b) May could herself call for a vote of confidence (c) parliament could present its own (cross party) plan and order May to carry out parliaments wishes. A confidence vote seems very likely, but May could win it by agreeing to do what parliament wants. The is big risk for both Labour and Conservatives is that it is very unclear which party would win a general election and its very unclear what the new PM that would inevitably be the result would do. The Conservatives could end up with their Members electing a new PM that could not control the Conservative MPs any better than May. If the Government entered a general election with May remaining as their candidate for PM its difficult to see how the Conservative MPs who had just expressed they had no confidence in her could back her. If May was still PM presumably her manifesto would be "vote Conservative so we can pass the May Deal", but as only around 25% of the public want the May Deal this hardly looks like an election winner. The alternative if May was still PM would be on a manifesto of "vote for the Plan B which I have been telling you for months is not possible". That does not sound like a winner either. Labour has a similar problem with the additional problem that the polls show them less popular than the Conservatives, so presumably to have a chance of winning an election they would need to change their Brexit policy (to being clearly against Brexit in the eyes of Remainers, but somehow being pro-Brexit in the eyes of Leavers. That seems to leave a very narrow policy option of the Norway+/Common Market 2.0) e.g. technical outside the EU, but with most of the advantages (and disadvantages) https://labourlist.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/Common-Market-2.0.pdf My guess is that an election will not take place, that A50 will be extended so a revised Withdrawal Agreement can be drawn up, and that a new detailed Political Statement for a new deal (quite likely based on Common Market 2.0) can be drawn up, and then a public vote to chose between Common Market 2.0 or remaining in the EU. (Other option such as No Deal Brexit will not get through parliament, a Canada ++ FT deal will cannot provide the frictionless trade needed to keep the Irish border as it is.

There can be no challenge to Theresa May's Prime Ministership from within her party for another 11 months. According to UK Conservative Party rules there cannot be a leadership challenge during the 12 months following the last spill. However, these are unpredictable times and May could choose to resign within the next 6 months if she came to believe either that it were in the best interests of her country or, that the parliament and her party were rendering her leadership ineffective. It may become increasingly difficult for her to steer the UK through Brexit in a way she believes is best for the country's economic future. Perhaps, she might rather resign the Prime Ministership than be remembered for the short to medium term economic pain that would inevitably follow a no deal Brexit. There's also a chance that the parliament might become so gridlocked that either May asks for another election or has that election forced upon her by the Crown. Her Majesty may also dismiss the May govt if the country become too politically and economically unstable. This happened in Australia in 1975.

First, there are three mechanisms for changing PM: 1) Resignation - this has happened 3 times since 1940 (18.8% of cases, given 16 PMs since then). I view this as quite unlikely, given that it would signal the end of May's political career and would be an exit in extreme duress, destroying her tattered political legacy 2) Vote of No Confidence: Conservatives held such a vote on 12 Dec 2018, which PM May survived. According to party rules, another vote may only be held after 1 year. A Vote of No Confidence could be triggered by Labour, but given Labour's 229 seats in Parliament (of 650), they would need a minimum of 34.5% of Conservatives to support, assuming all Lib Dems and other party members support the motion, which is highly unlikely. 3) Agreement for a new general election: this would require 2/3 vote of all MPs - extremely unlikely, given the split in Parliament.

The Brexit, however it unfolds, will be highly unpopular with ~50% of the population and trigger a no-confidence vote that May will not survive. The general assumption will be that somebody from Labour will do better - where "better" may mean holding a 2nd referendum on the issue. The thing that might keep May in power is continuing negotiations beyond the current deadline.

In spite of May's tenacity I am finding it difficult to see how she can hold on. There cannot be much chance that she can get her EU Withdrawal bill through parliament (close to 0%) and if she does not surely she should resign (10%). If she does not resign surely Corbyn would call for a Parliamentary Vote of No Confidence (30%) which he might or might not win (50% win). If May won a Parliamentary Vote she could carry on, if not she has a couple of weeks to try and sure up her support before having another vote. So there is only about a 20% chance that May would lose both No Confidence Votes. Even if she does lose both she is still in the game because then there would need to be a General Election and according to the polls the Conservatives could still be the biggest party (not because May is viewed as a good PM, but because Corbyn is not viewed as potentially a good PM). My feeling (based on no data) is that more voters could hold their nose and vote Labour to stop May, than could hold their nose and vote Conservative to get May, but this might be because most people I talk to see Corbyn as useless, but May as dangerous. Corbyn's mistakes could be put right later, May's would last for a generation. So my thinking is if May can get past a Parliamentary No Confidence Vote she could hang on. If she loses a Parliamentary No Confidence Vote she might hang on in an election. Although May has got a lot of Conservatives MPs who have no confidence in her, they see that voting No Confidence in the Government (as opposed to voting No Confidence in May as Conservative Leader) would probably mean Corbyn became PM and there was a Labour government. So Conservative MPs are unlikely to vote with the opposition in a Parliamentary No Confidence Vote, An additional reason for Conservatives not to vote No Confidence in the Government is that the outcome could lead to a General Election in which MPs could lose their seats. But its difficult to see how May could command day to day control of her party if she fails to get the Withdrawal Agreement through, and difficult to see how she gets thrown out!

Theresa May is one hell of a political survivor. She's survived years of very serious criticism, a flubbed slap election in which she decreased her majority, opportunism in her own party, and most recently a no confidence vote. Another no confidence vote cannot take place for a year, so Brexit cannot dethrone her procedurally, she would have to step down. Here are the scenarios I imagine:

I think there are multiple stages to consider in this question: 1) votes of no confidence: Labour has tabled a motion against PM May, minor parties a motion against the whole government https://www.reuters.com/article/us-britain-eu-snp/minor-uk-opposition-parties-table-vote-of-no-confidence-in-government-idUSKBN1OH2L8 2) Brexit deal vote: For simplicity, I assume that a Brexit deal vote has a 65% probability of passing, and assume that if it does not pass May will resign 3) general election vs existing parliament votes in a new PM: I am assuming there won't be much difference in the probability of scenarios for a) May resigns or b) is forced out of office by a vote of no confidence in herself only. Parliament could vote in a new PM without a general election. They could also decide to call a general election even though they don't have to (I estimate 70% probability for this). If the vote of no confidence in the government as a whole is successful, there has to be a general election. 4) In case of a general election, assuming that it will be a tight race, so 50% Conservatives win, 49% Labour wins, 1% other (see below) (http://ukpollingreport.co.uk/ , thanks @Futureseeker) 5) In either a general election or new PM election case, I am assuming an outside chance of 1% for PM from neither of the big parties.
Given the Brexit mess, May's position looks shakier every day, thus > 50% for a replacement. Given that Conservatives hold relative majority the most likely replacement is someone from that party.

Since 1945 there have been 15 prime ministers, serving just under 5 years in office on average. Base rate of changing prime minister is 20% in any given year (i.e. 10% in any six month period). 9 of 15 prime ministers have been Conservatives, but May's recent no confidence vote victory modifies this.
